posts.name: AryanPatel
posts.cooked: Hi there! I'm just curious—did most teams CAD their own elevator or did they just model one after an Andymark or WCP product? Some of these elevators look pretty complex to CAD, so I was wondering. If that's the case, what are some good resources to get started?

posts.name: Karl Olson
posts.cooked: The website [https://www.frcdesign.org/](https://www.frcdesign.org/) provides a solid foundation for mastering CAD creation for FIRST Robotics Competition (FRC) robots.

posts.name: Pizzatc
posts.cooked: We CADed our own design based on other teams' models. However, to get started, I would recommend using the FRC Design Learning Course available at https://www.frcdesign.org. Olsonkarlp beat me by five seconds.

posts.name: Isaac Proctor
posts.cooked: This year, we purchased a **WCP** 2-Stage GrayT Cascade Elevator. We copied WCP's CAD files from their website and entered the part studios to adjust dimensions and components to fit our robot. We created a separate assembly within the part studio to add brackets and related components. Our measurements were based on our master sketch, and we integrated everything into our full assembly just like the rest. It took a lot of time to get the CAD working properly, but it ended up functioning well without major issues. This was our first year using parametric CAD, so I'm not sure if this method is the most efficient, but it worked adequately for us.

posts.name: Calvin Selin
posts.cooked: Our elevator code was a nightmare. I would highly, highly recommend coding your own.

posts.name: Kade Rabe
posts.cooked: generally, you cAD it yourself, but you could definitely base your work heavily on the existing CAD they provide. this also provides greater flexibility to adjust or approach tasks differently.

posts.name: Camren
posts.cooked: We found a configurable CAD model in OnShape that used the SDS elevator blocks. This will be the last time I put in a large configurable assembly into my CAD. It was a major pain to make any modifications to it because the feature tree was almost impossible to navigate, and we almost cut the wrong size pieces because at one point the configuration got reverted to default. I think 4 hours of work to CAD it up statically at the start would have saved us 20 hours of fussing around with the configured version throughout the season.

posts.name: James Lyon
posts.cooked: I disagree. I think large configurable assemblies are great, especially when it’s something like an elevator, as it allows teams to quickly add complex mechanisms to their CAD. If the assemblies aren't configured properly, working with them can become cumbersome. In fact, creating multiple parts that don't reference each other in the same Part Studio can indeed complicate things unnecessarily. Regarding configurations reverting to default values, Onshape has a specific behavior where every time you insert something into an assembly, you must explicitly set the configurations; otherwise, it defaults. This seems to align with what you're describing. While this can be frustrating, I wouldn’t be so quick to never use large configurable assemblies again—they can still be a significant help.

posts.name: Camren
posts.cooked: I think that is a valid take; the way you're describing it is essentially a more complex Kraken CAD. Following through on your point further, I think teams could dedicate entire off-seasons to building up repositories of configurable sub-assemblies of parts they know they have on the shelf. This would give teams an advanced version of Kraken CAD to start their seasons. However, I think this would only work if the models were built correctly and you had a principal mentor in place to ensure continuity through student turnover.

posts.name: James Lyon
posts.cooked: That's a good way to put it. The advantage is it can actually be used for a finalized CAD.

posts.name: Nick Aarestad
posts.cooked:
We utilized a blend of Commercial, off-the-shelf (COTS) components and custom-designed elements to create our 2025 elevator. This approach was chosen due to its ability to balance standardization with uniqueness, ensuring efficiency without compromising on customization.

Similar to other projects, I noticed that fully configurable elevator systems can sometimes present challenges. To address these issues, we adopted a mixed strategy for our 2025 robotic project, incorporating both configurable and non-configurable components.

For anyone interested in exploring this further, detailed documentation on several configurable components can be found here: [Onshape](https://cad.onshape.com/documents/7722c0b90ba6a929c0694963/w/2b746a7eb29b8b3b9a448ec5/e/cacaab859003ee08e56eaf77). This platform is widely recognized as the fastest-growing CAD system globally, with millions of active users.

Additionally, the CAD files for the elevator can be accessed here: [Onshape](https://cad.onshape.com/documents/4ebbae2e91626ba9ad771692/w/c9a70e069478c0ba4c88899a/e/6553770592d7a73f4eddc3a3). Once logged in, users can explore a variety of customizable and fixed components designed to meet diverse needs.

CAD, especially when dealing with complex systems like elevators, can seem overwhelming to newcomers. However, breaking down the problem into manageable parts is an effective strategy. One such key component is the end/stop assembly, which can be reused across multiple parts of the elevator. While not physically constrained in our design, aligning them logically ensures consistency and reduces potential issues, particularly in rope-based elevators where maintaining pulley alignment is crucial.

Exploring these resources will reveal a mix of configurable and non-configurable parts tailored to various applications. Elevator design often requires bold decisions, and while leveraging existing COTS solutions can provide valuable insights, there's frequently a need for slight modifications to suit specific requirements. Understanding these nuances allows teams to implement solutions efficiently during critical periods.

Good luck with your endeavors!
